data.title: WASHINGTON ON THE BRAZOS
data.meta_description:
34 reviews and 148 photos of WASHINGTON ON THE BRAZOS "I dragged my boyfriend to see the bluebonnets, and when we saw the signs for this park, we thought, why the heck not?! 

It is FREE to walk around the grounds and see the beautiful wildflowers. They do have a donation box which I recommend putting a few dollars into - most parks (at least where I'm from in California) charge at least $5 just to park your car in a park!

There are some museums on site which require paid admission, but prices seemed very reasonable.They also offer tours for history buffs who want to know everything there is to know about the birthplace of Texas. 

The people working were incredibly nice and helpful. We followed the trail they suggested and saw some beautiful wildflowers, including bluebonnets!

Know before you go: wear closed toed shoes (the path is gravel perfectly sized for getting stuck in sandals) and bring mosquito repellent! There were a lot of butterflies and other insects flying around, which is good if you are into butterflies, and terrifying if you hate things flying around your face.

Much of the trail is exposed and it was quite toasty so I'd also recommend bringing sunscreen, a hat, and water.

Signs indicate that dogs are allowed on the trails, although we didn't see any.

The one disappointment: the independence building is a reconstruction of what the original might have been like - not the remains of the real one."
